<div class="rules-container">
    <div class="rules-header">Concept of Death in Islam</div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>Death – A Transition, Not an End</h3>
        <p>In Islam, death is a transition to the eternal life of the Hereafter. It marks the end of worldly trials and the beginning of the soul’s journey back to Allah ﷻ.</p>
        <blockquote>“Every soul shall taste death.” (Surah Aal-Imran 3:185)</blockquote>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>The Temporary Nature of This Life</h3>
        <p>This worldly life is a test. Our deeds, intentions, and faith will determine our standing in the Hereafter. Believers are reminded to stay mindful of Allah and prepare for this journey.</p>
        <blockquote>“He who created death and life to test you [as to] which of you is best in deed.” (Surah Al-Mulk 67:2)</blockquote>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>At the Time of Death</h3>
        <p>The angel of death (Malak al-Mawt) is sent to extract the soul. For the believer, this process is peaceful, while for the disbeliever, it can be difficult.</p>
        <blockquote>“Indeed, those who have said, ‘Our Lord is Allah’ and then remained steadfast – the angels descend upon them, [saying], ‘Do not fear and do not grieve but receive good tidings of Paradise.’” (Surah Fussilat 41:30)</blockquote>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>The Life of the Grave (Barzakh)</h3>
        <p>After death, the soul enters Barzakh, the stage between death and resurrection. It is a place of rest or trial, depending on the person’s faith and deeds.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>Remembering Death</h3>
        <p>Death serves as a reminder of our temporary life and encourages us to live righteously.</p>
        <blockquote>“Remember often the destroyer of pleasures – death.” (Tirmidhi)</blockquote>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>Duties of the Living</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Praying (du‘a) for the deceased</li>
            <li>Giving charity on their behalf</li>
            <li>Doing righteous deeds in their name (e.g. building a well, Quran distribution)</li>
            <li>Paying any debts or unfulfilled obligations of the deceased</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>Conclusion</h3>
        <p>Death is not something to be feared, but to be prepared for. It is the beginning of our return to Allah. Islam teaches us to live with purpose, sincerity, and awareness of the Hereafter.</p>
    </div>

